<DOC><DOCNO> AP881108-0190 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-08-88 2047EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-JusticeFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0710 11-08 0347</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Justice Fire, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0710,0353</SECOND><HEAD>Government Building Fire Forces Transfer Of 1,800 Jail Inmates</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to CORRECT that fire forced transfer of1,800 inmates, sted 1,600, UPDATES with 36 people treated for smokeinhalation and inventory to be taken to determine loss of narcotics.Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The inmates...'</NOTE><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A fire started by a welder's torch in anevidence storage room at the Los Angeles County Hall of Justiceforced authorities to evacuate the building Tuesday and transfer1,800 jail inmates.   No one was seriously injured, but 30 firefighters and sixsheriff's employees were treated at hospitals for smoke inhalation,said Fire Department spokesman Dean Kathey.   Sheriff Sherman Block said narcotics, particularly cocaine,burned in the 45-minute blaze. Authorities will conduct an inventoryof the evidence to determine how much was lost, he said.   The blaze began in a seventh-floor storage room that containeddocuments and narcotics seized as evidence in sheriff's departmentinvestigations, said Vince Marzo, a city fire department spokesman.   Greg Acevedo, a fire dispatcher, said officials were concernedthat runoff water from the storage room might be contaminated by thenarcotics evidence.   Heavy, black smoke poured from the building, in the Civic Centerdistrict of government and public buildings.   An estimated 1,800 county prisoners were housed in the upper sixfloors of the 13-story building, which is more than 60 years old,county officials said.   The inmates were transferred to the county's main jail, the Men'sCentral Jail, a few blocks away, Sheriff Sherman Block said at animpromptu news conference.   The sheriff said there was no automatic sprinkler system in thebuilding, although he noted that fire hoses were installed on eachfloor.   The building was originally the county's main justice building,holding jail, courts and law enforcement offices. Now, courts are inother buildings and the hall is used primarily as headquarters ofthe sheriff's department and a jail for short-term prisoners.   The building shares a busy intersection with City Hall, theCriminal Justice building and the U.S. District Courthouse.</TEXT></DOC>